  "prompt": "Who all can apply the title \"Er.\" as a prefix for their names?",
  "response": "The title \"Er.\" is typically used as a prefix by individuals who are registered or licensed engineers in countries where this practice is recognized. The specific rules and regulations governing the use of \"Er.\" can vary by country, but generally, it is used in the following contexts:\n\n1. **Registered Engineers**: In countries like India, Nepal, and some others, \"Er.\" is used by engineers who are registered with the relevant engineering council or licensing body. For example, in India, engineers registered with the **Institution of Engineers (India)** or the **State Engineering Council** may use the title.\n\n2. **Professional Engineers (PE)**: In some countries, such as the United States or Canada, the title \"PE\" (Professional Engineer) is used instead of \"Er.\" Only those who have obtained a PE license through a formal process, including education, examination, and experience, can use this title.\n\n3. **Engineering Graduates**: In some regions, engineering graduates may use \"Er.\" as a prefix to indicate their academic qualification, even if they are not registered or licensed. However, this practice is less formal and may not be legally recognized.\n\n### Important Notes:\n- The use of \"Er.\" without proper registration or licensing may be considered unethical or even illegal in some jurisdictions.\n- Always check the specific rules and regulations of the engineering council or licensing body in your country to determine eligibility for using the title \"Er.\" \n\nIf you are an engineer, ensure you meet the necessary qualifications and certifications before using the title.",
